{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778536803,"nonce":"anhAzHxcO4N59kG252jazSzvHvg=","title":"Analytical bridge for rlrmp cost function (no-jerk variant)","message":"The existing analytical Riccati implementation (`9a0558e`, closed) reproduces C\u0026S 2019 with their cost function: state quadratic with `(t/N)^6` discount + control quadratic. To bridge between C\u0026S analytical results and our trained networks, we want a SECOND analytical run with rlrmp's cost structure.\n\n## Scope\n\nClassical LQR / H∞ Riccati for rlrmp's uniform-L2-quadratic cost. NO jerk term (jerk is not classical-Riccati-tractable; would need numerical optimization). Variant to derive analytically:\n\n- Position cost: uniform `effector_hold_pos = effector_pos_running` (equal weights, target-switching at go-cue)\n- Velocity cost: 0 (no `effector_hold_vel`)\n- Control cost: `||u||²` (controller force squared)\n- `(t/N)^k` schedule optional, depending on what the lit-replication 6-cell matrix reveals about which shape is operative\n\nCompare Δv prediction against trained no-jerk networks (cells 4-6 of the upcoming 6-cell matrix). The result tells us:\n\n1. Does rlrmp's cost-function structure produce a Δv signature analytically?\n2. How does it compare to C\u0026S's `(t/N)^6` back-loaded prediction?\n3. Is the trained network's behavior closer to the our-cost analytical or C\u0026S's?\n\n## Why analyses, not training methods\n\nThis is an analysis applied to a training method's results — a reference simulation for comparison, not a training method itself. Lives on `4d38c15`.\n\n## References\n\n- `9a0558e`: C\u0026S faithful Riccati (closed).\n- `03a148a`: Replicate C\u0026S 2019 analytical LQG vs H∞ Riccati.\n- `3f111e9`: Hyperparameter sweep on analytical Riccati (cost-function exponent).","files":null}]}